{"schema_version": 2, "source_hash": "696143dbc1df9e48", "candidate": {"id": "cand-008", "name": "Eleanor Hawkins", "raw_cv": "ELEANOR HAWKINS\neleanor.hawkins@email.com | London, UK\n\nPRINCIPAL DATA ENGINEER\n\nPROFESSIONAL SUMMARY\nPrincipal-level data engineer with 9 years of experience building enterprise data infrastructure across banking, insurance, and payments. Deep expertise in Spark, dbt, and data mesh architecture. Led teams of up to 8 engineers.\n\nEXPERIENCE\n\nPrincipal Data Engineer \u2014 HSBC, London (2020\u2013present)\n- Designed the bank's Group Data Platform architecture (data mesh) serving 40+ consuming teams\n- Led a team of 8 engineers through a 2-year platform modernisation programme\n- Introduced dbt at scale, defining standards adopted bank-wide\n- Delivered SOX compliance data lineage project on time and under budget\n\nStaff Data Engineer \u2014 Lloyds Banking Group, London (2016\u20132020)\n- Senior engineering lead on credit data infrastructure and model feature stores\n\nData Engineer \u2014 Xchanging (now DXC), London (2015\u20132016)\n\nSKILLS\nPython, SQL, dbt, Spark, Snowflake, BigQuery, Airflow, Kafka, Terraform, Data Mesh architecture, team leadership\n\nEDUCATION\nBSc Mathematics \u2014 University of Nottingham (2012\u20132015)\n\nRIGHT TO WORK\nBritish citizen", "raw_linkedin": "Principal data engineer and data platform architect with nine years in financial services. I've spent my career in environments where data accuracy and governance are existential concerns \u2014 banking and insurance. Currently leading a data mesh transformation at HSBC. Strong in Spark, dbt, and Snowflake. Based in London, happy to be in the office. Looking for principal or staff engineer roles where I can keep hands-on while having architecture influence.", "raw_interview_transcript": "Interviewer: Eleanor, you have an impressive background. Tell me about the data mesh work at HSBC.\n\nEleanor: It's been the most complex and rewarding thing I've worked on. Data mesh is easy to describe and very hard to implement in a large bank \u2014 there are so many legacy systems, organisational politics, and compliance constraints. We've been at it for two years and we're probably 60% of the way there. The shift to product thinking for data has been the biggest cultural challenge.\n\nInterviewer: What's drawing you to this particular role? We're a much smaller company than HSBC.\n\nEleanor: That's exactly the draw. I've spent four years in big bank politics and I want to work somewhere where I can make decisions faster and see the impact more directly. Apex's payments focus is familiar territory.\n\nInterviewer: The office setup is five days a week at Canary Wharf.\n\nEleanor: Fine by me. I'm in Elephant and Castle so that's straightforward.\n\nInterviewer: Let's talk about compensation. We have a budget up to \u00a385,000.\n\nEleanor: I appreciate the transparency. I'm currently on \u00a3105,000 at HSBC, and with my level of experience I'd need at least \u00a3105,000 to consider a move. I'm not in a position to take a significant pay cut even for a role I find interesting. Is there any flexibility on the budget?\n\nInterviewer: Unfortunately our budget for this role is firm at \u00a385,000 maximum. It sounds like there may be a gap here.\n\nEleanor: I think there might be, yes. I don't want to waste either of our time if the compensation can't be made to work.", "years_experience": 9.0, "skills": ["Python", "SQL", "dbt", "Spark", "Snowflake", "BigQuery", "Airflow", "Kafka", "Terraform", "Data Mesh architecture", "team leadership"], "industries": ["banking", "insurance", "payments", "financial services"], "seniority_level": "principal", "management_experience": true, "education_level": "bachelor", "career_trajectory": "ascending", "interview_score": 0.78, "culture_fit_score": 0.72, "constraints": [{"id": "b1e4b07f", "type": "hard", "side": "candidate", "category": "compensation", "description": "Current salary at HSBC is 